<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 93 / GPA rescue hits legal snag
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEGOTIATIONS between GPA Group, the aircraft leasing company, and GE
Capital, the financial services arm of General Electric of the US, have run
into legal difficulties, delaying completion of the deal.
Before any agreement is signed GE Capital has to satisfy itself that it will
not be held liable for GPA's Dollars 5.2bn (Pounds 3.5bn) debts.
The US group has agreed in principle to buy Dollars 1.35bn of GPA's
aircraft. The aircraft would be managed, with GE's own fleet, by a new
subsidiary run by several of GPA's existing executives.
GE Capital's lawyers want to satisfy themselves that the new subsidiary
could not be held responsible - by GPA's unsecured creditors for instance -
for any of the group's liabilities. Under the terms of the agreement the
debt would be left with GPA.
GE Capital's lawyers also wish to ensure that directors of the subsidiary
could not be seen to be 'shadow directors' of GPA, and thereby responsible
for the company's obligations. A senior negotiator in the deal said: 'GE's
lawyers are crawling all over the deal to ensure they can safely separate
the obligations from the operations.'
Mr Jack Hersch, research director at MJ Whitman, which specialises in
selling bank debt, said: 'It is a very fine line to separate the
responsibility for the operations from the obligations to repay debt'.
GPA's advisers had hoped to file the prospectus with Irish Companies House
on July 16 and hold an extraordinary general meeting this week.
Both companies now hope to solve the legal difficulties by early next month
followed by an EGM in October. GPA needs the support of holders of 75 per
cent of its shares.
The delay has also caused concern to some of the group's shareholders, who
are reluctant to raise all of the additional Dollars 150m originally
requested by GPA to ensure the deal's success. However, GPA now believes it
no longer needs to raise as much because its cash balances are stronger.
GE Capital's option, which is for 65 per cent of the group, could rise to 80
per cent if shareholders fail to raise additional funds.
Bankers to the group, however, remain confident that some shareholders, if
not as many as first envisaged, will take part in the underwriting.
The option, which is costing GE Capital less than Dollars 200m, can be
exercised as late as March 31, 1997.
</TEXT>
