<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 93 / Dunhill warns on currency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A PROFITS warning from Dunhill Holdings and the cost of the luxury goods
group's foreign exchange policies yesterday cast a small shadow over the
corporate restructuring proposed by Richemont of Switzerland.
Richemont, controlled by the Rupert family of South Africa, wants to split
off the group's tobacco arm, Rothmans International, and combine its two
luxury goods businesses, Luxco and Dunhill, into Vendome. Dunhill is at
present a 57 per cent owned subsidiary of Rothmans.
Dunhill said that because 95 per cent of its business arose outside the UK,
it hedged future income up to 30 months ahead. Recent currency movements -
notably the strengthening of the yen - meant its sterling profits for
1993-94 and 1994-95 would be Pounds 19m and Pounds 13m lower than without
the hedging.
Operating profits were also likely to fall this year because of the drop in
Japanese consumer spending, weakening economies in Germany, Italy and Spain,
and only hesitant recoveries in the US and UK.
Details, Page 16
Lex, Page 14
