<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 93 / Bosnia talks expected to restart: Serbs accept UN
arbitration but air strike preparations continue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER, HAIG SIMONIAN and GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA, MILAN, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL mediators expect the Bosnian peace talks to resume today after
the Serbs agreed to accept United Nations arbitration in a dispute over the
extent of Serb withdrawal from a strategic peak near Sarajevo.
The more hopeful signs came as Nato countries pressed on with military
preparations for possible air strikes against the Bosnian Serbs.
A United Nations spokesman in Geneva said that the mediators, Lord Owen and
Mr Thorvald Stoltenberg, expected a resumption this afternoon of the talks
between leaders of the three warring factions in Bosnia.
But Bosnia's Moslem president Alija Izetbegovic, who has boycotted talks for
12 days, gave no confirmation that he was ready yet to change his stand.
He reiterated earlier that he would not return to the Geneva talks with
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and the Bosnian Croat leader Mate Boban
until the Serbs completed their withdrawal from Mount Igman overlooking
Sarajevo.
However, UN arbitration in that dispute might end the impasse.
The UN spokesman in Geneva confirmed last night that Bosnian Serb forces
remain deployed in 'areas of Igman Mountain', but added that the troops 'did
appear to have left the centre of the area from which they agreed to
withdraw'.
Mr Karadzic claims that Serb forces can remain on parts of the peak seized
before a ceasefire agreement reached July 30. But after intensive sessions
with the international mediators, he agreed last night to accept UN
arbitration as 'binding' on a disputed line beyond which Serbs should
withdraw.
With Nato preparations mounting, General Francis Briquemont, commander of UN
forces in Bosnia, flew to a Nato air base in Italy yesterday to discuss the
logistics of air strikes with Admiral Jeremy Boorda, Nato's commander of
Allied Forces Southern Europe.
Italy later announced that it was sending more troops to reinforce its
border with former Yugoslavia to protect against possible reprisals in the
event of Nato bombing raids.
In a further escalation of tensions, Mr Karadzic was reported to have told
an Austrian newspaper that he would try to acquire nuclear weapons to carry
out attacks if the west pressed ahead with military action.
The comments were due to be published in Austria today.
But a spokesman for Mr Karadzic last night denied he made the threat.
</TEXT>
