<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 93 / French reserves fall by FFr190bn: Deficit explains country's
caution in reducing interest rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING, JAMES BLITZ and QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, LONDON, BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bank of France has been left with a substantial net deficit in its
foreign currency reserves as a result of its attempts to keep the franc
inside the European exchange rate mechanism at the end of last month.
Figures issued yesterday by Bank of France showed that the country's net
reserves fell by almost FFr190bn (Pounds 21.64bn) in the week to August 5,
leaving the central bank with a deficit of more than FFr180bn in its foreign
exchange holdings.
The franc slipped against the D-Mark yesterday after the central bank
figures were issued.
The Danish krone also fell sharply against the D-Mark amid signs that
Denmark also needed to replenish its foreign exchange reserves after the ERM
crisis.
The drain on French reserves will have been due almost entirely to the
central bank's intervention in the currency markets to try to keep the franc
above its former ERM floor against the D-Mark.
On July 29 alone, economists estimate the central bank spent more than the
FFr160bn used to defend the franc in its previous crises. The total amount
of reserves used by the French authorities in the recent crisis is estimated
at more than FFr305bn.
The franc closed yesterday at FFr3.514 against the D-Mark, about a third of
a centime down on the day. But at one stage, the currency was being bought
at FFr3.52.
The reserves data helped to explain France's cautious approach to reducing
interest rates since the widening of fluctuation bands within the currency
system on August 2. Economists said that if the French authorities were to
lower interest rates, the currency could fall against the D-Mark - but the
central bank would have no reserves with which to support the exchange rate
through intervention.
The krone came under even heavier selling pressure inside the ERM, in spite
of Denmark's announcement of a large offering on the bond market to help
replenish its foreign exchange reserves. The bond issue, worth SFr1bn
(Pounds .4bn) came in the wake of a Pounds 1.3bn Eurobond sterling offering
last week.
But news of this latest bond tender could not prevent the krone falling in
London to a close of DKr4.1135 against the D-Mark from a previous DKr3.406.
The size of the capital flows is expected to spur attempts by European
Community members to strengthen their defences against currency speculators.
Currencies, Page 32
</TEXT>
