<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 93 / Bomb-damaged church to reopen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE of the oldest victims of the Baltic Exchange bomb is about to resume
duties. After careful restoration of its stained-glass windows and
stonework, the 12th-century St Andrew Undershaft is to reopen on September
1, 18 months after the IRA bomb that exploded in the heart of the City.
The church, in St Mary Axe, was about 100 yards from the centre of the blast
and its three large stained-glass windows were severely damaged. Yesterday
craftsmen were beginning the final phase of replacing the most badly damaged
panels of the window in the church's east wing.
The repair work has been undertaken by Goddard and Gibbs, the stained-glass
manufacturers. Its craftsmen removed the remains of the 15ft by 30ft windows
to the company's workshop for the painstaking task of reconstruction.
Because few photographs of the windows existed, the blast area had to be
carefully swept for traces of glass fragments. For the east window, the
designers had to work from a small photograph showing just one-third of the
100-year-old depiction of the crucifixion and resurrection. Much of the time
since has been spent redesigning the missing elements.
Installation will take up to three weeks as the workmen replace each panel
individually. These are slotted into the grooves of the surrounding
stonework and held in place by horizontal supporting bars. Copper tie bars
are used for additional support.
So far one window, on the north side of the church, has been fully restored.
However, the third and west window was almost completely blown out. Its
restoration is not expected to be completed before October.
Mr Christopher Borst, Goddard and Gibbs sales director, said that the main
difficulty had been in trying to track down detailed photographs of the
windows.
He said: 'The information has not been comprehensive and there have been
several large holes where we have been working fairly much in the dark.'
The company is one of about a dozen stained-glass manu-facturers and
restorers in the UK.
</TEXT>
