<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 93 / Move to curb NHS drugs bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE National Health Service will no longer pay for nicotine smoking
cessation patches, under proposals announced by the government yesterday,
Paul Abrahams writes.
The proposal is part of a larger package detailing products which doctors
will no longer be allowed to prescribe, part of the government's efforts to
control the burgeoning NHS drugs bill which last year grew 14 per cent.
The products range from Perrier, Malvern and Evian mineral waters to Ambre
Solaire sun cream, aromatherapy massage oil, Johnson &amp; Johnson's prickly
heat powder, and Pickles' nail bite lotion.
Details of the drugs on the first of 10 categories on the new NHS blacklists
were also given. The category, for topical anti-rheumatics, included 40
medicines.
Among them were American Home Products' Algipan, SmithKline Beecham's Ralgex
and its Beecham analgesic cream, Boots' Menthol and Wintergreen Embrocation,
and Culpepper's Healing ointment.
Companies and patient groups now have a month in which to respond.
