<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 93 / Water bills 'hit poor hardest'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POOR HOUSEHOLDS spend proportionately more on water and sewerage charges
than the rich, and this would change little under the alternatives being
considered for a new way of charging.
This is a central conclusion of a report by the Institute for Fiscal Studies
for Ofwat, the water regulator, yesterday.
At present Water charges are based on the rateable value of a property, a
system which has to be replaced by the year 2000. This system is seen to
have two principal weaknesses: single people living in large houses pay more
for water than large families in small houses, and it provides no incentive
for people to conserve water.
The study looked at four alternative ways of charging:
A licence fee under which all households pay the same.
A licence fee would have to be set at around Pounds 152 a household to
generate the present water industry revenues. But poorest households
currently pay an average Pounds 127.49 for their water so they would lose
out. By contrast the richest households pay just under Pounds 180 so they
would be big gainers. Overall, 41 per cent of households would be better
off.
A charge based on the number of people in a household.
Such a charge would have two elements, a Pounds 6 standing charge and Pounds
55.96 a person. Poorest households would pay nearly Pounds 127, almost
exactly what they pay now, but the richest would pay about Pounds 144. The
big gainers would be pensioners whose charges would fall from Pounds 146 to
Pounds 105.
A charge based on the type of property.
Charges banded by house type showed poorest households paying nearly Pounds
140 and the richest Pounds 160, nearly Pounds 20 less than now. Pensioners
would end up paying slightly more.
A charge based on the volume of water consumed by each household.
If meters were introduced to charge for water by volume, poor households,
which include most pensioners, would gain slightly, so would the richest
households because of the switch from their high rateable values.
Middle-income houses, however, would end up paying more.
The report does not say which system is preferable. But it points out that
more households gain than lose on charges based on the number of people in
the household.
Mr Ian Byatt, the director-general of Ofwat, favours metering because
Ofwat's studies have shown that people think water should be paid for by
volume.
He welcomed the report and said: 'It is interesting to see that a number of
household types would gain from metering - including some on lower incomes.
But I recognise that there would also be losers.'
Each of the water companies in England and Wales can choose its own charging
method. So far only one company, Anglian Water, has made a choice, in favour
of metering.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4941 Water Supply.
    P4952 Sewerage Systems.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
