<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 93 / Leading condom maker claims technical advance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON International Group, the health products and toiletries company which
is the world leader in branded condoms, yesterday said it had developed a
polyurethane material which represented an advance in condom technology.
LIG said the material, trademarked Duron, had advantages over latex -
normally used to make condoms - which made it more acceptable to users. The
group's shares closed up 12p to 213p.
It claims 23 per cent of the world's branded condom market, with names such
as Durex in the UK, Ramses and Sheik in North America, Hatu in Italy and
London in Germany.
Dr Bill Potter, the group's scientific affairs director, said Duron was
twice as strong as latex and could therefore be made much thinner, giving
greater sensitivity. It was also, transparent, odourless, and hypoallergenic
 -less likely to cause allergic reactions than latex - and not damaged by
oil-based lubricants. It has all the attributes of latex in terms of
reliability and effectiveness against pregnancy and disease, including Aids,
he said.
Dr Potter said that in tests, Duron had proved it could be an effective
barrier to viruses much smaller than HIV, the Aids virus.
Mr Tony Butterworth, chief executive of LIG, said the group had spent Pounds
10m during the past five years developing the product, including building a
pilot plant at its Cambridge research facility.
This would produce condoms for test marketing, which would start in the US
next year and be extended to other countries depending on regulatory
approvals. The material has already won US Food and Drug Administration
clearance, and key parts of the manufacturing process have been patented.
Mr Clive Kitchener, LIG director of marketing, said the condoms would sell
at a substantial price premium to latex ones, but market research showed
people would pay more for a better product. He said the group still expected
growth in the latex condom market and that condoms made from Duron would
expand the market, attracting new users.
Mr Butterworth said the group would build one or more full-scale production
units once results from test marketing were clearer.
</TEXT>
