<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 93 / NHS ends nicotine patch payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE National Health Service will no longer pay for nicotine smoking
cessation patches, under proposals announced by the government yesterday.
This is in spite of the government's declared policy that the number of
smokers in the UK should be cut by a third by the year 2000.
The proposal is part of a larger package detailing products which doctors
will no longer be allowed to prescribe, part of the government's efforts to
control the burgeoning NHS drugs bill which last year grew 14 per cent.
The products range from Perrier, Malvern and Evian mineral waters to Ambre
Solaire sun cream, aromatherapy massage oil, Johnson &amp; Johnson's prickly
heat powder, Pickles' nail bite lotion, and Smith &amp; Nephew's Simple Talcum
Powder.
Details of the drugs to be included in the first of 10 categories on the new
NHS blacklists were also given. The category, for topical anti-rheumatics,
included 40 medicines.
Among them were American Home Products' Algipan, SmithKline Beecham's Ralgex
and its Beecham analgesic cream, Boots' Menthol and Wintergreen Embrocation,
and Culpepper's Healing ointment. Companies and patient groups now have a
month in which to respond.
The Department of Health said the advisory committees deciding which drugs
should be included in the other nine categories were due to report before
the end of the year. These include oral contraceptives, anti-diarrhoeals,
hypnotics and anxiolytics, and skin diseases.
Dr Brian Mawhinney, minister for health, said: 'Our proposals will not
disadvantage patients. A full range of other products remain available on
the NHS.'
Nicotine patches had a role to play in helping some people stop smoking, but
people who could afford to smoke could also afford to buy products that help
them give up, he said.
The main smoking cessation products no longer available on prescription are
were Nicabate, marketed by Marion Merrell Dow of the US, and Nicorette, sold
by Kabi of Sweden. Nicotinell from Ciba in Switzerland was already not
available on the NHS.
</TEXT>
