<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 93 / Accounts panel acts on criticism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FINANCIAL Reporting Review Panel, the accounts watchdog, is considering
providing more information on the reasons behind its rulings.
The initiative is one of several changes being considered as part of its
first procedural overhaul since it began operations two years ago.
The move follows representations from the Institute of Chartered Accountants
in England and Wales calling for greater information on the review panel's
decisions.
It marks a greater openness about the reasons for its judgments on
companies, which are given in public announcements.
Some accountants have criticised the verdicts of the review panel, and have
said it was difficult to assess the judgments without knowledge of how they
were reached.
The issue was highlighted in a decision this week by the institute after it
had investigated the panel's criticism last year of Trafalgar House, the
construction, property, shipping and hotels group.
Trafalgar House was forced to amend its 1991 accounts after criticism from
the panel of its decision to charge a Pounds 102.7m deficit on a revaluation
of properties directly to reserves. The institute ruled that there was no
case to answer against any of its members.
It is believed that the institute was provided with no information on the
reasons behind the review panel's verdict, with which Trafalgar House
complied after an initial refusal.
Other changes to the panel's procedures being considered include ways to
simplify and speed up administration of cases, and greater opportunities to
clarify facts before cases are formally undertaken.
The changes are likely to debated and introduced over the next two to three
months.
</TEXT>
