<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 93 / Interest loss of Pounds 4.5m in port sell-offs criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS and RACHEL JOHNSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DELAYS DURING the privatisation of the first five trust ports cost the
government at least Pounds 4.5m, the National Audit Office, the
public-spending watchdog, says in a report today.
Sir John Bourn, comptroller and auditor-general, said although the five
sales were completed by March last year, generating a Pounds 169m levy for
the government, only Pounds 54.4m was paid to the Department of Transport at
the time.
The remaining Pounds 114.6m was left unpaid until February and March this
year because of disagreements between the ports and the department over the
expenses incurred. The interest lost, assuming simple Treasury bill rates,
was at least Pounds 4.5m for the six months to last December alone.
The office says the department should have sought legal advice on whether it
had the right to require further interim payments, and it suggests changes
in the process when further ports are privatised.
Yet the office's general conclusion was that the department had been
'successful in this first stage of the privatisation of the trust ports'. It
backed the controversial decision to sell the Tees and Hartlepool port
authority to the second-highest bidder, Teesside Holdings, for Pounds 180m.
Sir John repeated the department's judgment that to reject the port
authority's recommendation solely in order to maximise the levy proceeds
would be hard to justify.
Tees and Hartlepool, Clyde, Forth, Medway and Tilbury all privatised
voluntarily last year. They account for more than half the turnover of the
15 ports whose turnover exceeds Pounds 5m at 1991 prices. These ports can be
forced to be sold to the private sector under the Ports Act 1991. The five
privatisations took place before the act came into force.
Gross proceeds from the sale of the five ports came to Pounds 380m. The
government received Pounds 169m of the proceeds as statutory levy, while the
cost of the sale amounted to Pounds 12.8m. The port authorities spent Pounds
9.6m of this, while Pounds 2.2m went to management and employee buy-out
teams. The remaining Pounds 1m was paid to the department's advisers.
The department's marketing produced a 'sound basis for competition', with
the four tendered sales producing between six and 19 inquiries. The fifth
port, Forth, was sold by flotation.
However, Sir John said competition was limited in the final bidding for
Clyde, where two of the three bids were unsatisfactorily low, and for
Medway, where a withdrawal left only one bidder.
Department of Transport: the First Sales of Trust Ports. HMSO, Pounds 5.45.
</TEXT>
<XX>
