<TEXT>
ACCOUNTANTS are highly critical of the effectiveness of the new standards
being produced by the Auditing Practices Board, says a survey released
yesterday.
Fewer than half of about 100 auditors questioned believed any of the board's
proposed guidelines were sufficiently precise to form the basis of audit
regulation.
The survey, published in the trade newsletter True &amp; Fair, is one of the
first attempts to assess the work of the board, which was created two years
ago to redraft auditing standards in the UK.
