<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 93 / Venezuela economic reforms on way
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOSEPH MANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CARACAS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
VENEZUELA'S congress has granted President Ramon Velasquez powers until the
end of this year to introduce economic measures by decree. His government, a
transitional administration due to step down in February, asked for special
powers to tackle a series of problems, including the growing fiscal deficit.
The powers will allow the president to introduce:
a sales tax and a tax on the assets of private companies;
reform of the financial system, including opening up banking to foreign
investment;
initiatives to help farmers;
reforms of tax legislation aimed at raising revenues and applying corporate
taxes to private investors in the oil and gas sectors;
a change in the law for selling off the Aeropostal airline.
A joint session of congress also approved a long-awaited privatisation law
reform, aimed at speeding the process.
President Velasquez, who took office on June 5, has said his interim
government will pave the way for a new president, scheduled to be elected in
early December. The new sales and asset taxes will benefit the current
administration only a little but should provide the next government with a
stronger fiscal base.
The administration is facing several economic problems. Revenues from oil
exports, which provide most government income, have fallen because of weak
international oil prices; the government is projecting a fiscal gap of
around Dollars 3.7bn (Pounds 2.5bn) for 1993. Inflation stands at around 36
per cent a year, and economic growth has dropped sharply from last year's
7.3 per cent.
</TEXT>
