<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 93 / Rexrodt plans measures to speed privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NEW laws to accelerate privatisation by Germany's 16 state governments, and
local authorities, were promised yesterday by Mr Gunter Rexrodt, economics
minister.
He criticised sharply the growth of creeping public ownership through the
powerful state banks, singling out especially WestLB, the public sector bank
in North Rhine-Westphalia.
Clearly intending to step up public pressure for more privatisation at state
and local government level, he warned that he would introduce 'instruments
of torture' to get the process moving. The spread of public ownership
through state banks was in complete contradiction to the federal
government's privatisation policies.
Mr Rexrodt was not precise on the measures he intends, but said his ministry
was working on the legislation. He proposed legal budgetary 'guidelines' as
one measure, and compelling all public authorities to investigate private
solutions to tasks currently conducted by publicly-owned bodies.
His attack on North Rhine-Westphalia, and WestLB in particular, will
certainly be warmly greeted by the private banking sector, which has been
very critical of the growth of the state banks.
WestLB is 43 per cent owned by the state government. Mr Rexrodt listed
shareholdings of more than 10 per cent in nine separate public companies,
including Preussag (32 per cent), the Horten retail chain (26 per cent) and
VEW, the electricity generator (11 per cent), with a total value of more
than DM3bn (Pounds 1.2bn).
The bank also has unlisted shareholdings in the travel groups LTU, TUI and
Thomas Cook, and other companies.
He also called for Germany's powerful savings banks to be privatised 'as far
as possible', in order to remove competition distortions in banking.
As far as the federal government was concerned, he said, early privatisation
of Deutsche Telekom, the state telecommunications concern, had top priority.
Plans for selling off service areas, such as airports and ports, should be
accelerated.
</TEXT>
