<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 93 / Ford may reshuffle German posts as cost pressures mount
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORD-WERKE, the German subsidiary of the US motor group, yesterday refused
to comment on reports that its American-born chairman is to be replaced by a
German, writes Christopher Parkes.
Mr John Hardiman, head of Ford-Werke for five years, is to return to the US
and his post will be filled by Mr Albert Caspers, according to the industry
newsletter, PS Report.
Mr Caspers, currently vice-president responsible for engineering and
manufacturing at Ford Europe, will shortly be joined in the German
subsidiary's headquarters by Mr Heinz Soiron, Ford's general manager in
Spain, the newsletter added.
The reshuffle did not indicate that there was any dissatisfaction with Mr
Hardiman, 59, who has worked in Europe for Ford for more than 30 years, PS
Report suggested.
It was prompted more by the need, detected by Mr Jacques Nasser, the new
chief at Ford Europe, for a technical leader to oversee sharp cost
reductions in line with those under way throughout the German motor
industry.
Mr Caspers has been in charge of all 24 Ford plants in Europe since 1989.
Mr Soiron, recognised as a high-flier in Ford Europe, is expected to be
appointed as sales director and Mr Caspers' deputy.
Mr Roger Leite, current sales chief of Ford-Werke, is expected to be
appointed northern group director of Ford Europe, the newsletter said.
Mr Hardiman would 'probably' return to the US.
</TEXT>
