<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 93 / C&amp;G will stop endowment mortgage sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHELTENHAM &amp; Gloucester, the UK's sixth largest building society, is to stop
selling endowment mortgages.
The move follows criticism of mortgage lenders because of the high charges,
including commissions, on endowment policies and their uncertain final
returns.
Yesterday C&amp;G said it would stop sales of life assurance after its five-year
exclusive distribution agreement with Legal &amp; General ended in November. It
would concentrate instead on the sale of interest-only and repayment
mortgages.
Mr Andrew Longhurst, C&amp;G's chief executive, said the society preferred to
let customers choose their own method of repayment. C&amp;G decided in 1990 to
stop urging its customers to take endowment mortgages. Currently one in 12
of C&amp;G's new borrowers is sold one, compared with an industry average of 69
per cent.
Customers who wish to have an insurance product will be referred to local
independent financial advisers who are responsible for referring roughly 60
per cent of C&amp;G's existing mortgage clients.
Mr Longhurst said C&amp;G's low cost base meant it did not need the extra income
from the sale of insurance products to remain profitable. 'We've come to the
point where we don't want to play that game any more,' he said of the
society's role as a 'tied agent' of Legal &amp; General.
In recent years, life insurers have competed intensely to sign up building
society outlets to sell their products exclusively and have rewarded them
with handsome commissions. Bancassurance, the sale of financial services
products through bank-type outlets, is regarded as the cheapest form of
distribution.
Building societies, however, have been criticised for urging unnecessary
insurance products, particularly endowment mortgages, on borrowers.
Discounted mortgages often require the borrower to sign up for an insurance
product. Mr Longhurst said C&amp;G would still offer discounted products.
Legal &amp; General said it was sorry to see the end of the relationship with
C&amp;G, but noted that 'the changing nature of C&amp;G's business spread makes it
no longer appropriate nor cost effective for a tied relationship'.
Maverick society, Page 6
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Cheltenham and Gloucester Building Society.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
