<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 93 / British Coal seeks up to 15 pit closures in 8 months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COAL wants to close up to half its 30 working pits within eight
months after a thorough investigation of the energy market persuaded it that
only about a dozen pits have a long-term future.
British Coal's latest prognosis is far worse than anything it has
acknowledged publicly to date. It means a significantly larger contraction
of the industry than the government admitted was in prospect even last
October, when public anger forced a retreat on widespread pit closure plans.
In considering whether to sanction 15 closures in the current financial year
ending on March 27, as British Coal would prefer, ministers will be wary of
stirring controversy at a time when they need maximum Conservative backbench
support for coal privatisation this year and next.
The Department of Trade and Industry is thought to have accepted the
economic case for the 15 closures. Hesitation in implementing them stems
from concern about the political consequences.
Ministers and British Coal are, however, acutely aware that delay will store
up problems for the 12 or so core pits that are likely to comprise the
company when it is privatised.
British Coal's stockpiles, already above 14m tonnes, are growing at up to 1m
tonnes a month. The higher they rise the greater the likelihood that private
sector operators will add to the closure list in future years.
Mr Gerard McCloskey, disclosing British Coal's thinking in his Financial
Times International Coal Report weekly facsimile to subscribers, says that
not even 12 pits will survive long term if new private sector mine owners
opt to meet contracts from stocks.
Pressure is building for a closures announcement as early as next month. The
simultaneous closure of 15 pits is unlikely following the reaction to last
October's announcement.
More likely, British Coal will announce fewer than half a dozen closures at
first. More would follow piecemeal throughout the remainder of the financial
year, with public reaction influencing how many can close.
British Coal's problems stem from the coal white paper in March which
reprieved 12 pits earmarked for closure in October 1992 but did little to
find a market for their coal.
Since then, the electricity generators, which are British Coal's main
customers, have shown reluctance to buy coal above existing contracts.
Moroever, sales to generators under these contracts will fall from 40m
tonnes this year to 30m in 1994-95, making closures among the previous core
of 19 pits inevitable.
The government is committed to offer to the private sector any pits no
longer wanted by British Coal in the run-up to privatisation. Companies will
be offered subsidies for any coal they can sell to the generators before
privatisation.
British Coal last night refused to comment on how many closures would be
necessary.
</TEXT>
