<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / (CORRECTED) UK Company News: Cable and Wireless wins
Hungarian contract
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 13th August 1993) appended to this article.
CABLE AND Wireless, the UK telecommunications group, has won a licence for a
national paging network awarded by the Hungarian government.
The licence was awarded to Radio Telecommunications Company, a joint venture
in which C&amp;W has a 49 per cent stake. Other partners include the state
telecommunications company.
The contract is a further boost to C&amp;W's ambition to become a significant
force in Hungary, whose state telecommunications company looks set to become
the first of those in east European to be privatised.
The contract will complement RTC's existing cellular mobile contract. It is
investing Pounds 27m in infrastructure for the cellular network, which is
due to launched at the end of this year.
C&amp;W's has other east European ventures in Belarus, Russia, and the Baltic
states. However, its main investment focus is in the UK, through Mercury
Communications, and in Asia Pacific, where it has a majority stake in Hong
Kong Telecom.
CORRECTION
A company in which Cable and Wireless has a 49 per cent stake was this week
awarded a licence to provide a national paging service in Bulgaria, not in
Hungary as reported in some editions yesterday.
</TEXT>
