<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow sets new record as
bondyields tumble
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
ANOTHER record-setting day saw US share prices soar yesterday afternoon on
the back of tumbling bond yields, with strong gains in semiconductor stocks
offsetting some losses in healthcare issues and mining stocks, writes Karen
Zagor in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average added 10.62 to set a new record of
3,583.35. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was 1 higher at
450.46, while the Amex composite eased 0.32 at 438.87, and the Nasdaq
composite firmed 1.69 at 718.77. Trading volume on the NYSE was more than
266m shares, and rises outnumbered declines by 1,057 to 856.
In the absence of any significant economic reports yesterday, market
movement was dominated by sector news.
The semiconductor sector was bolstered by Tuesday's report of unexpectedly
strong orders for chips. On the big board, shares in Motorola firmed Dollars
1 3/8 to Dollars 96 1/4 , Texas Instruments gained Dollars 1 to Dollars 77
1/2 after hitting a 52-week high earlier in the day, and Advanced Micro
Devices rose Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 29 5/8 . Intel added Dollars 1 7/8 to
Dollars 58 3/4 in Nasdaq trading.
Shares in mining companies moved lower in tandem with falling gold prices.
In Comex trading, the December gold price was quoted Dollars 5.70 an ounce
lower at Dollars 378.70. American Barrick lost Dollars 3/8 to Dollars 25 1/8
, Newmont Mining fell Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 50 3/8 and Amax eased Dollars
 1/8 to Dollars 24 5/8 .
Among other featured issues, Eaton Corp added Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 45 3/8
, partly recouping its Tuesday losses of Dollars 1 1/4 following news that
the company has entered a definitive agreement to buy Westinghouse
Electric's distribution and control business for Dollars 1.1bn, plus the
assumption of liabilities. Shares in Westinghouse slid Dollars  1/8 to
Dollars 15 3/4 .
In the tobacco sector, RJR Nabisco Holdings held steady in spite of reports
in the Wall Street Journal that the FTC plan to recommend a ban of the
company's popular Joe Camel advertising campaign.
Shares in health maintenance companies tumbled after Donaldson, Lufkin &amp;
Jenrette cut its ratings on the group. Oxford Health Plans plummeted Dollars
8 1/4 to Dollars 62 3/4 , Ramsay-HMO dropped Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 28,
Healthsource fell Dollars 4 3/4 at Dollars 37 1/8 and United Healthcare
tumbled Dollars 6 3/4 to Dollars 52 3/4 .
Chemical Waste Management lost Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 9 3/8 after the
company said it was suspending its quarterly dividend payments because of
uncertain market conditions.
Equitable Companies climbed Dollars 4 to a 52-week high of Dollars 25 1/4
after the company turned in second quarter earnings of Dollars 47.5m against
an operating loss of Dollars 18.8m a year earlier. Salomon Brothers lifted
its rating on the stock to 'buy' from 'hold', reflecting the improved
performance and predictions of improved sales momentum in the second half.
Canada
TORONTO stock prices closed mixed in busy trading, as the market eased after
three days of solid gains.
According to preliminary figures, the TSE-300 index fell 12.55 points, or
0.31 per cent, to 4,015.89, but advancing issues outnumbered declines 372 to
340. Volume was 66.431m shares, up from 63.038m shares on Tuesday, and
trading value rose to CDollars 810.1m.
</TEXT>
