<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: US Midwest crop losses
estimated at Dollars 2.5bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Mike Espy, US agriculture secretary, said yesterday his country's maize
and soyabean harvest would be adequate to meet world demand, despite summer
floods that had devasted large portions of some of the most fertile crop
land.
The US Department of Agriculture conducted its most extensive survey ever of
crop conditions during the first week in August, and yesterday released the
results.
Tha agency said crop losses due to flooding and drought in Midwestern states
amounted to Dollars 2.5bn. And it revised its estimate of the maize crop to
7.423bn bushels, down 22 per cent from last year's harvest and below private
forecasters estimates of about 7.5bn.
Despite the drop, Mr Espy said he expected little movement in maize prices
today. Although this year's crop will be short, there are ample maize
supplies in storage to meet customer needs. The US has 2.124 billion bushels
of maize carried over from last year's bumper harvest, and export orders for
delivery after harvest have been lagging.
The agriculture department put this year's soyabean harvest at 1.902bn
bushels, about 13 per cent smaller than in 1992. Soyabean traders had been
anticipating a figure closer to 1.857bn and are expecting soyabean futures
prices to fall by about 10 cents a bushel on the Chicago Board of Trade
today. Soyabean futures for November delivery closed up 10 cents at Dollars
6.83 in anticipation of the report yesterday.
Soyabean prices have been declining in fits and starts since the high of
Dollars 7.56 1/2 on July 19. Traders said any shortfall in the US crop would
be eagerly replaced by Brazilian production, a negative prospect for US soya
farmers.
In a survey of the nine Midwestern states hit hardest by Mississippi and
Missouri river floods, the department said farmers would harvest 145.6m
acres, 7.8m less than expected in June. About 2.8m acres were never planted
because of wet conditions, and about 5m were planted but cannot be
harvested. The agency said production figures were also cut by hot, dry
weather in the US southeast this summer.
Pointing out that the government crop survey was completed last week, Mr
Daniel Basse, analyst at the Chicago research company AgResouces, said: 'The
real focus now will be how many bushels we can add to these figures as we
head into harvest.' Mr Basse said that sultry conditions in the western
maize belt during the past week had been ideal for maize and soyabean
development, but the crops were still racing an early frost and actual
production figures were far from certain.
</TEXT>
