<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / International Company News: MCI president Akerson quits
telecoms industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR DAN AKERSON, president of MCI, the US's second-biggest long-distance
telephone company, is leaving to head General Instrument, a maker of
transmission equipment for cable television with a market value of nearly
Dollars 4bn.
He will also become a general partner in the leveraged buy-out firm of
Forstmann Little, which took control of General Instrument in 1990.
Mr Akerson, 44, was made president and chief operating officer of MCI only
last year. He had won the support of Wall Street for his hard-driving
attitude, and for the agreement in June to bring in British
Telecommunications as a 20 per cent shareholder in MCI.
Mr Akerson said he had not been looking to leave MCI, but had been drawn
away by the opportunity to lead General Instrument as it develops in the
field of interactive media.
Mr Bert Roberts, MCI's chairman and chief executive, added that the
financial package had also tempted Mr Akerson away. His new remuneration was
not disclosed, but last year his salary and bonus at MCI came to Dollars
830,000, and he was given restricted stock in the company worth another
Dollars 790,000 and options over 46,000 shares.
Analysts said that the departure resulted in part from the fact that Mr
Akerson's path to the top at MCI was blocked by the 51-year-old Mr Roberts.
Both men denied there had been any disagreement over strategy. MCI, which
was notified of Mr Akerson's intention to leave only on Tuesday, said it had
not yet decided whether to replace him, or whether to take the opportunity
to reorganise management.
General Instrument said Mr Donald Rumsfeld, 61, a former US defence
secretary, would step down as chairman and chief executive after Mr Akerson
joins the company at the end of August, but would remain a director.
MCI shares fell on the news but later recovered to close at Dollars 28 1/4 ,
up Dollars  5/8 on the day. General Instrument's shares lost Dollars 2, to
Dollars 47.
McCaw Cellular Communications and PacTel, a unit of Pacific Telesis Group,
have received regulatory approval to combine their interests in San
Francisco, San Jose, Dallas, and Kansas City, and Kansas, into a 99-year
joint venture.
McCaw and PacTel said they would each have equal ownership of the venture.
</TEXT>
