<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / International Company News: SKF doubles losses but sees
improvement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SKF, the world's leading roller bearing manufacturer, said yesterday that
losses more than doubled in the first six months, but it noted that its
performance had started to improve following rationalisation.
The group's loss after financial items for the period was SKr469m (Dollars
58.66m), which was smaller than expected, compared with a SKr194m deficit in
the first half of 1992.
Sales rose to SKr14.53bn from SKr14.04bn, but adjusted for currency
movements and disposals they were down 8 per cent.
The group said its second-quarter loss fell to SKr114m from SKr355m in the
first quarter due to the drive to cut costs which it launched in 1990. For
the same reason, it expects its second-half results to be better than in the
first half - providing there is no further deterioration in its markets.
The first-half operating loss of SKr66m was aggravated by financial costs of
SKr403m, due to the depreciation of the krona and a SKr55m currency exchange
loss. In the same 1992 period, the operating loss was SKr46m and financial
expenses SKr148m.
The group's main bearings and seals business, which depends on the health of
the car and engineering industries, recorded a loss of SKr251m, after a
first-half 1992 profit of SKr156m.
SKF fears the market may not have bottomed in this sector, even though
volumes have remained unchanged for the last three quarters. 'The situation
is still fragile,' said a spokesman, who highlighted the group's exposure to
the recession-hit German market.
Weak industrial output in both Germany and France meant SKF recorded a loss
of SKr440m in these markets in the first half.
The outlook in other markets is brighter, however. In North America,
earnings and volumes picked up during the second quarter, while sales in
central and South America and Asia Pacific also develop-ed.
The company's other main business, Ovako Steel, managed to cut losses to
SKr224m from SKr319m amid signs that the demand for special steel products
was bottoming out and prices stabilising at low levels.
As part of its rationalisation programme, SKF has cut staff by 12,400 since
1990, reduced production by 20 to 25 per cent in response to lower demand,
and cut inventory levels by SKr2bn. The payroll has been reduced by 2,000 to
43,000 so far this year.
The company's shares rose SKr3 to close at SKr115 yesterday.
Lex, Page 14
</TEXT>
