<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / UK Company News: H&amp;C sells Malaysian quote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HARRISONS &amp; Crosfield, the agribusiness, chemicals and plantations group,
will gain more than Pounds 5m by selling the quotation of its Malaysian
rubber business.
In a complex deal announced yesterday, Harrisons is selling its 51 per cent
stake in Linatex for MDollars 5.25 per share, or about Pounds 14.7m, to
Phileo Assets of Malaysia.
The sale will be subject to Linatex, which produces rubber for industrial
use, selling all its assets and business to Harrisons for Pounds 10.2m.
Other conditions include regulatory and minority shareholder approval.
Under Malaysian regulations, Harrisons will eventually have to find a local
partner to take a minority stake in Linatex. Mr Graham Wickenden, group
finance executive, said that in previous cases in Malaysia a minority stake
was between 25 and 30 per cent. Based on the price paid by Harrisons, the
group will gain a further Pounds 2.5m to Pounds 3m on the sale of the
minority.
Phileo Assets intends to use the Linatex quote to take over Phileo Peregrine
Securities, an Ipoh-based stockbroker which is 30 per cent owned by Hong
Kong's Peregrine Group.
The move comes amid heavy trading in shell companies on the Kuala Lumpur
stock exchange over the last six months as businesses seek funds for
expansion. A recent report from Morgan Grenfell Asia shows that shell
companies are trading at a premium of between MDollars 40m and MDollars 50m
above net tangible asset value. Mr Wickenden said the Phileo offer was
pitched at MDollars 70m above the NTA of Linatex, placing the deal in the
top quartile of deals done to date.
</TEXT>
