<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / Westinghouse starts asset sales with Dollars 1.1bn division
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT and CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WESTINGHOUSE Electric, the troubled US conglomerate, is set to sell its
electrical distribution and control equipment business to Eaton Corporation,
the engineering group, for Dollars 1.1bn (Pounds 745m).
Cleveland-based Eaton is also assuming certain liabilities.
The sale is conditional on government approvals and the waiver by Germany's
Siemens of a 'right of first refusal'. Siemens, which was granted the right
in 1988, said it was 'looking to see how things develop'.
Westinghouse added it had been in close contact with the German company,
which should be in a position to make a 'prompt' decision. If the Siemens'
waiver is not received within 30 days, Eaton can terminate the deal. If the
sale goes through, it will be the first element in an asset-sale package
announced last November by Pittsburgh-based Westinghouse, which has been
dogged by bad property loans.
As well as quitting financial services, it revealed plans to sell four
non-strategic operations: the distribution and control business;
Westinghouse Electric Supply; the Knoll International office furniture unit;
and the Westinghouse Communities property development subsidiary. It pledged
to cut debt by more than Dollars 5bn in two years.
Mr Michael Jordan, who took over the chair in July, said the proceeds would
help pay down debt resulting from the financial services unit's losses.
The distribution and control business makes low-voltage circuit protection
equipment and employs about 12,500 people at 36 plants, mainly in North
America, South America and the UK.
Eaton said the Westinghouse operations would be combined with its industrial
control and power distribution business to create a division with sales of
about Dollars 1.6bn. Group sales should increase by about 25 per cent.
Last year, the company - best-known for the manufacture of truck
transmissions and axles, engines components and electrical equipment and
controls - had turnover of Dollars 3.87bn.
Eaton plans to fund the purchase initially via bank borrowings. However, it
added that it was also planning an equity issue.
Westinghouse shares closed down Dollars  1/8 at Dollars 15 3/4 , while Eaton
ended the day up Dollars  3/4 at Dollars 45 3/4 .
</TEXT>
