<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / Hospital audits to go to tender: Accountancy firms welcome
pilot scheme in market testing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AUDIT SERVICES for hospital trusts and local authorities are to be opened to
competition next year in a market testing exercise by the Audit Commission.
The move was immediately welcomed by large accountancy firms, many of which
are anxious for new sources of business.
Sir David Cooksey, chairman of the commission, which this year received
gross fee income of Pounds 76.6m for auditing public bodies with a total
turnover of about Pounds 85bn, announced today that the commission's
district audit service is to be made administratively separate.
The commission will then work as a purchaser of services provided by the
district audit service or outside accounting firms.
About 30 per cent of the commission's work is already shared between eight
firms of private auditors, and the district audit service itself contracts
out 15.3 per cent of its workload. However, rival bids are assessed only on
quality, and all firms are paid a uniform audit fee, making it 'very
difficult to pass on the benefits of competitive tendering', according to
Sir David.
Under a pilot scheme due to start in April next year, 2 per cent of the
commission's audit work will be awarded on the basis of price competition.
Most contracts will involve new National Health Service trusts, but some
local authority contracts will be included. The scheme will then be
monitored for at least a year before deciding whether to extend the
programme. Sir David said: 'We are able to do this because with the next
wave of trusts coming through in April next year there is an increase in
workload.'
He said the scheme remained on a limited scale because the review of local
government structure in England by Sir John Banham, former director-general
of the Confederation of British Industry, is still in progress.
'Once the outcome of the local government review is fully understood, a much
larger tranche will be put up for tender,' Sir David said.
Price Waterhouse was one of several large accountancy firms which expressed
interest in bidding for the new contracts.
Mr Gordon Cartmell of Touche Ross said: 'It is very early days but we are
interested in pursuing these contracts.' He said the firm would make a
judgment on each potential tender, based on what services it might be
excluded from by taking on the audits.
Auditors might, for example, be barred from offering computer consultancy,
tax advice or general management consultancy. The commission has promised
'full discussion' with interested parties before the first pilot.
Funds 'at risk' in opt-out schools, Page 6
</TEXT>
