<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / Japan trade surplus up 28% as weak demand damps imports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S trade surplus in July was Dollars 11.82bn (Pounds 8bn), 28 per cent
higher than in the same month of 1992, reflecting the weak demand for
imports from a still ailing domestic economy.
The surplus has risen year-on-year for 31 consecutive months. However, the
yen's strength is slowing export volume, which is up only 2.1 per cent.
The surplus also appears to be near its peak, which would be welcomed by
Japan's new coalition government.
Japanese industry leaders expressed regret at the sharp appreciation
yesterday of the yen, which closed in Tokyo at a record of Y103.77 to the
dollar, compared with Y104.47 on Tuesday, and said the figure did not
reflect the real health of the economy.
Mr Gaishi Hiraiwa, chairman of the Keidanren, the federation of economic
organisations, said the yen had 'deviated from reality' and that the
continuing appreciation had put great pressure on Japanese companies, which
already face a fourth year of falling profits.
Exports during July rose 9 per cent to Dollars 32.18bn, while imports grew
by a slim 0.4 per cent to Dollars 20.37bn, although both figures reflected
exchange rate movements.
The finance ministry said the average yen value for exports in July was
Y108.21 to the dollar, compared with Y125.57 a year earlier.
The surplus with the US rose 22.7 per cent to Dollars 4.68bn, the 16th
consecutive month of expansion, but Japan's surplus with the European
Community fell 19.5 per cent to Dollars 2.01bn. Seasonally adjusted, the
surplus rose from Dollars 8.64bn in June to Dollars 11.17bn last month.
Trade with China continues to expand at a remarkable rate and after almost
five years of deficit Japan now has a bilateral surplus.
Exports to China rose 68.7 per cent to Dollars 1.77bn, while imports were
17.1 per cent higher at Dollars 1.6bn. Last September, Japan had a deficit
for the month of Dollars 634m.
Indicating the demand from an overheated Chinese economy, car exports rose
five times, steel exports 167 per cent, and electric machinery 62 per cent.
However, the figures hardly reflect the true growth of Japanese exports
because they do not include goods shipped through Hong Kong.
