<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / Fraudster flees to northern Cyprus
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A TURKISH Cypriot businessman serving a five-year jail sentence for tax
fraud is believed to have fled to northern Cyprus after failing to return
from weekend home leave.
It will embarrass the authorities, who are already smarting from former
Polly Peck chairman Mr Asil Nadir jumping bail and fleeing to northern
Cyprus three months ago while facing theft charges over his collapsed
business empire.
Mr Gultekin Mustafa Ben left Stanford Hill open prison in Kent, on Saturday
morning for a five-hour family visit.
A police spokesman in northern Cyprus, which has no extradition treaty with
the UK, told Reuters news agency that a man calling himself Mr Ben arrived
there on Sunday with his wife.
Mr Ben was jailed for five years and fined Pounds 100,000 in March after a
five-month trial relating to a Pounds 12.5m VAT and PAYE fraud involving
clothing factories, illegal immigrants and false invoices. Mr Ben, an
accountant, had set up bogus businesses selling false invoices to his
clients.
