<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / Timex brings forward Dundee plant closure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TIMEX IS planning to close its troubled printed circuit board plant in
Dundee within weeks, several months earlier than expected, the company said
yesterday.
But the closure of the factory, after 47 years of operation, looks unlikely
to end one of Britain's longest and most bitter industrial disputes for many
years, as strike leaders vowed to step up a boy-cott of Timex products in
continental Europe and North America.
'The company's decision to shut the plant reflects the success of our
world-wide campaign against them,' said Mr Charlie Malone, Timex strike
committee chairman. 'We don't intend to end it until the name of Timex is
tarnished.'
The strikers will meet today to discuss their next moves.
Timex management announced two months ago its intention to stop production
in Dundee by the end of the year after workers rejected a peace formula to
resolve the eight-month-old strike which followed their mass dismissal for
refusing to accept cuts in their terms and conditions of employment. The
strike was accompanied by large demonstrations in Dundee, with occasional
violent scenes outside the plant.
The company has decided to bring forward the date of the plant's closure and
yesterday 93 workers who replaced the strikers received their redundancy
notices.
Timex said the remaining 170 replacement workers and 97 clerical and
managerial staff would also go as soon as Timex's business customers have
found alternative suppliers for printed circuit boards.
The AEEU engineering and electrical union is unlikely to continue
recognising the dispute and paying the strikers Pounds 30 a week once the
plant is shut, although national officials want to ensure that Timex honours
legal obligations over the pension fund for its ex-employees. The strike
committee's fund-raising efforts in Britain and elsewhere are said to have
produced about Pounds 200,000.
Over the past four weeks a delegation has been travelling around the US,
building support to confront Timex through a boycott of its products.
Contact has also been made with unions in Mexico, the Philippines and France
where Timex continues to have production plants.
A number of US unions including communication workers, steel workers, miners
and machinists have mobilised backing for the Timex strikers.
The AFL-CIO union federation in Washington is hoping the strike committee
will be able to give evidence to a congressional committee on its
experiences to support the striker replacement bill which US unions hope
will secure congressional approval this autumn.
That measure is designed to make it unlawful for a US employer to sack all
its workers if they go on strike. Mr Malone also said a legal action against
Timex in the US courts was being discussed under the 1988 Omnibus Trade Act,
which prevents US companies discriminating against workers in their overseas
plants.
</TEXT>
