<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / Headhunters back on the trail
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCY KELLAWAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECESSION took a heavy toll from headhunters, with the size of the
European executive search market shrinking by nearly a quarter last year,
says a report from the Economist Intelligence Unit. But the market has
stabilised and is forecast to pick up next year.
The report estimates that consultancy income last year was about Dollars
700m-Dollars 800m (Pounds 475m-Pounds 545m) - 20 per cent to 25 per cent
less than the previous year. The fall was most marked in middle management,
where headhunters' revenues dropped by more than 40 per cent. Headhunting of
top-level executives was relatively unaffected.
The report shows that the structure of the industry is changing, with
consultants increasingly offering multinational clients cross-border
searches. Headhunters are also diversifying into related areas such as
interim management, management audit and assessment, executive selection and
headhunting non-executive directors.
The survey ranks headhunters by revenue, and names the Swiss consultancy
Egon Zehnder as the largest with nearly 10 per cent of the market. It is
followed by GKR Neumann and Amrop International.
The two largest markets are Germany and the UK. In Germany the top 10
companies have combined revenues of Dollars 93m. The corresponding figure
for the UK is Dollars 78m. The top 10 consultants' revenues in France, the
third-largest market, were Dollars 43m.
Executive Search in Europe: Choosing and Using a Headhunter. Economist
Intelligence Unit, 40 Duke Street, London W1A 1DW. Pounds 135/Dollars 210.
</TEXT>
