<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / Cardiff mail strike called 'unnecessary'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROYAL MAIL yesterday denounced as 'totally unnecessary' the nine-day dispute
by 900 postal staff in Cardiff over the introduction of a new shift system.
The dispute has paralysed the letter service in south Wales, and Royal Mail
has called on the Union of Communication Workers to put a proposed peace
formula to the strikers for their approval.
Management said the proposed framework agreement it negotiated with the
union's executive had been turned down by the local branch officials.
Royal Mail said: 'There is no justification for this dispute. A framework
for a settlement has been worked out between Royal Mail and UCW national
executive members. We are deeply disappointed this framework has been
rejected by the local UCW leadership who must shoulder the blame for the
continuation of this dispute.'
Mr Les Parry, an executive member, denied the union had agreed any
framework. He said: 'Negotiations have been going on slowly but there has
been nothing to put to the union locally.'
Royal Mail said last night that about 2,500 postboxes had been sealed. It
advised those wishing to send documents to Companies House in Cardiff to
send them instead to Companies House in London.
</TEXT>
