<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / Up to 25% of shops robbed in past year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A QUARTER of shops in some parts of London have been victims of a robbery or
attempted robbery in the past year, according to a report published
yesterday by the Police Foundation, the independent research organisation.
The report, in conjunction with the University of Sheffield, highlights
crime affecting retailers. Mr Stanley Kalms, chairman of electrical retailer
Dixons, warned in June that shops were being forced to adopt 'vigilante
tactics' on crime, which was costing Dixons alone Pounds 20m a year.
The report says a quarter of London shopkeepers and 17 per cent in the
Midlands had experienced a robbery or attempted robbery with a knife, gun or
imitation gun in the last year.
The report also highlights a lack of contact between the police and some
victims. Although offences such as robbery were normally reported to the
police, shopkeepers in the Midlands said they rarely had any other contact
with their local police and many had negative views of policing.
Mr James May, director-general of the British Retail Consortium, said the
report reinforced the consortium's own findings. He said a nationwide sample
of 4,000 retailers with fewer than 50 staff found 1,317 incidents of serious
violence reported last year.
Violent Crime In Small Shops. Police Foundation, 1 Glyn St, London SE11.
Pounds 16.95.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
