<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / BCCI lawsuit wins backing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TOUCHE Ross, the liquidator of Bank of Credit and Commerce International,
has received what it considers a powerful mandate to pursue its legal action
against the Bank of England.
More than 5,000 depositors have signed and returned agreements to assign
claims worth Pounds 400m in all to the liquidators. This is substantially
more than was thought necessary to justify pursuit of the action, according
to a letter sent out by the liquidators.
The Bank of England has been granted an extension until September 1 to serve
its defence of the action. Originally the defence should have been made by
July 5 but the Bank asked for more time.
Depositors have been told that a civil court decision in Luxembourg, which
is needed before payments can be made from the proposed compensation
agreement, will not be made until October 27.
Touche Ross has been frustrated by the time taken by the Luxembourg court to
consider the agreement. The court has found only two and a half day's court
time since May for legal arguments.
The compensation package worked out between the liquidators and BCCI's Abu
Dhabi majority shareholders has been consistently opposed by a number of
creditors. However, a large majority of those who replied when canvassed
voted to accept the deal in which Abu Dhabi would contribute a minimum of
Dollars 1.7bn. The referendum had been demanded by the Luxembourg court.
The delays meant that staged payments of Dollars 800m in December 1992 and
Dollars 500m in June this year, promised by Abu Dhabi into the pooling
agreement, did not go ahead because they were conditional on the approval of
the agreement in the UK, Luxembourg and the Cayman Islands. The package has
already been approved in British and Cayman courts.
Liquidators have three principal civil suits outstanding. One is against The
Bank of England; another is against the National Commercial Bank of Saudi
Arabia and Sheikh Khalid Bin Mahfouz, its former chief operating officer,
who is also a former shareholder of BCCI; the third is against the former
BCCI auditors, Price Waterhouse and Ernst and Whinney (now Ernst and Young).
Ernst and Whinney audited part of the bank until 1987.
The action against the Bank of England is unprecedented and may rest on the
liquidators' ability to prove that the Bank was negligent in not acting
earlier against BCCI when it told of problems in 1985.
</TEXT>
