<DATE>930812
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / Tension high as Nigeria braces for protests: Stay-aways and
demonstrations have been called across the country
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ADAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SENSE of foreboding is almost palpable as Nigeria prepares for three
days of protest which could as easily tilt the country towards instability
as thrust it towards democracy.
Armed soldiers were posted at main intersections in Lagos yesterday. Shops
and offices closed early. Every bus heading out of Lagos was laden as
thousands of workers sent families and belongings to the safety of their
home towns and villages before the campaign gets underway today.
Infuriated by President Ibrahim Babangida's annulment of the June 12
presidential poll, the Campaign for Democracy - an informal coalition led by
civil rights activists, has called for a protest without precedent in the
country's post independence history.
Stay-aways, rallies and acts of civil disobedience have been called across
the country, to press home demands that General Babangida fulfil his pledge
to hand over to an elected civilian government on August 27.
Campaign organisers said yesterday the protests would go ahead despite the
government's threat to impose a state of emergency. 'The protests are still
on,' said Mr Livinus Ede, a CD official. 'The government statement has
nothing to do with it.'
But the days ahead could demonstrate the vulnerability of the opposition
rather than undermine the position of a seemingly intransigent general,
either wedded to power or fearful of the consequences of surrendering it.
The protests so far have been loud, but discordant. The two permitted
opposition parties are weak, the poorly organised trade union movement faces
high unemployment, the civil rights campaigners have few resources. The
ex-generals who have joined in the call for Gen Babangida to step down, fear
the bloody consequences of confrontation.
For all those contemplating action, the memory of the the civil war over
Biafra in the 1960s may mute the protest. The carnage and starvation that
cost hundreds of thousands of lives may be history, but the spectre of
secession is real even to the post-war generation.
Whether Yoruba people from the south, Ibo from the east, Hausa-Fulani from
the north, or a member of a minority tribe required by realpolitik to take
sides, the fragility of the Nigerian federation remains an abiding concern.
All the main opposition players - leaders of the Social Democratic party,
the National Republican Convention, and retired General Olusegun Obasanjo,
head of state from 1976 to 1979 and chairman of the Association for
Democracy - are aware of this fragility.
The ethnic and religious fault line which could split Nigeria is blurred, as
the presidential poll showed. Chief Moshood Abiola, the SDP's victorious
presidential candidate, is Yoruba, but a Moslem, and has his stronghold in
the south but won substantial support in the north.
Nevertheless, in times of stress the fault line runs between the largely
Christian south and the predominantly Moslem north, with both sides aware
that the vital asset is the oil in the east, responsible for over 90 per
cent of Nigeria's export earnings.
It is partly with these concerns in mind that the two main opposition
parties are holding back from the latest campaign. A similar call for
protests last month ended in violence in which up to 100 people died.
At the same, the opposition parties are intrinsically weak. Both were
created by the government. Neither has a distinct ideology, nor can they
generate mass appeal.
In the meantime, the SDP's leader is out of the country. Mr Abiola is in the
US rallying support for his presidency, and while he is away there is little
focus for resistance.
The deciding factor in the critical days ahead may be the role of the
unions. But they seem reluctant to act now, preferring instead to wait and
see what happens on August 27. The Nigeria Labour Congress has indicated
that it is prepared to call a national strike if there is no handover, a
threat backed up yesterday by Nigeria's biggest oil workers' union.
The organisers of this week's campaign, however, believe that pressure must
be exerted now if Gen Babangida is to fulfil his promise.
The exasperation of many Nigerians with these and other divisions and
uncertainties in the opposition ranks has brought respected non-partisan
national figures into the fray.
Most notable is Mr Obasanjo, who became the only Nigerian president to give
up power voluntarily when he ended 15 years of military rule in 1979. The
former general has done more than anyone in Nigeria to make clear to Mr
Babangida that his time in office has run out.
Having campaigned vigorously to persuade northern traditional rulers that
the issue transcends old rivalries, Mr Obasanjo seems to be throwing his
weight behind the civilian protest.
Near his farm in Otta near Lagos Mr Obasanjo holds meetings with a small
group of other former heads of state, generals and well known critics of the
regime.
In a speech last Monday, he stressed: 'The current political crisis is not
an ethnic or religious issue.
'As long as the military are at the helm,' he went on, 'democracy and good
governance elude us.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>NGZ  Nigeria, Africa.
</CN>
