<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / Romanian coalminers back at work as strike collapses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VIRGINIA MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUCHAREST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ROMANIA'S Jiu Valley coal miners returned to work yesterday after a nine-day
strike collapsed without apparently securing the large pay rises union
leaders had demanded.
The miners' union, the government, the Ministry of Industry and the RAH, the
state-owned company which administers the region's 13 coal mines, would not
release details of the settlement.
Rompres, the state news agency, said the union and the RAH had agreed on
monthly wages ranging from 146,000 lei (Pounds 122) for an unqualified
worker up to 207,000 lei for an underground miner, compared with an average
monthly wage of 224,000 lei which the union had demanded.
Before the strike, the region's 43,000 miners earned on average 40 per cent
more than other Romanian miners as well as receiving free coal, transport to
work, meals and subsidised electricity and rent.
The government said the strike had achieved nothing and it had stuck by its
original offer of an average monthly wage of 166,000 lei.
The union and the RAH had also agreed that 60 per cent of the 91bn lei
(Pounds 75.8m) government subsidy to the RAH for 1993 would be spent on
production and investment with the balance subsidising wages.
The Romanian train drivers' union yesterday launched its second strike in
two months, demanding new wage increases, causing further industrial chaos
just hours after the end of the strike by coalminers. Many main-line
stations were severely disrupted.
</TEXT>
