<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / Nato planners draw up Bosnia air-strike targets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LIST of Serbian targets for allied air strikes in Bosnia was being
finalised yesterday by military planners at Nato headquarters in Belgium.
But officials indicated that the allies were a long way from agreeing
precisely what action by Serbs in the former Yugoslav republic would trigger
air strikes - or what would avert them.
Under the terms of the military agreement approved by the Nato council on
Monday, air strikes can only begin if they have been specifically requested
and approved by both United Nations and Nato leaders and if the Serbs have
been given a clear warning, which effectively rules out 'surprise' attacks.
Nato planners have outlined various military options for action. The type of
operations understood to be under consideration include:
the bombing of artillery positions around Sarajevo, the Bosnian capital;
attacks on supply routes from Serbia;
attacks on Serb command and control positions and possibly attacks on the
Serbian stronghold of Pale near Sarajevo.
Military experts yesterday stressed that initially the most likely course of
action would be strikes around Sarajevo. Dr Jonathan Eyal, of the Royal
United Services Institute, an independent think-tank, said: 'If the
Canadians and others have signed up, it is unlikely that they have agreed to
anything more than bombing around Sarajevo, given that their troops are out
in Srebrenica.'
French and British diplomatic sources yesterday indicated that attacks on UN
troops remained the most likely reason for air strikes, and indicated that
in spite of the political significance that Mt Igman has assumed, a renewed
Serb assault on the mountain would not necessarily prompt action. However,
US officials have indicated that continued expansion of Serb territory could
be a reason for action.
</TEXT>
