<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 93 / Manufacturing recovery wavers: Business leaders lack
confidence in economy despite growing strength of equities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH and MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EXPECTATIONS about a strong manufacturing recovery have slipped back in
several UK regions, according to a Confederation of British Industry survey
published yesterday which underlines fears that the economic upturn may be
slowing.
While indicating that weak export demand from the rest of Europe is holding
back growth, the survey said manufacturing order books in six out of the 11
regions had fallen from levels four months ago.
The report said the expected drop in export orders across the country had
hit especially hard in three regions which up to now had been leading the
recovery - Yorkshire and Humberside, East Midlands and Wales.
Companies in three other regions - south-west and north-west England and
Northern Ireland - also expect falls in export orders over the next four
months.
The findings from the survey, conducted jointly with Business Strategies, an
economics consultancy, were supported by views from senior UK business
executives who said the recovery was far from robust and might not be
sustained in the second half of the year.
Mr Richard Freeman, chief economist at ICI, said demand in the
industrialised world continued to be 'very patchy', echoing a warning on
Tuesday by BOC Group, the industrial gases company.
Sir Anthony Gill, chairman and chief executive of engineering company Lucas
Industries, was 'cautious' about a UK recovery because signs of domestic
growth had not been matched elsewhere in Europe.
Mr Roger Hurn, chairman and chief executive of Smiths Industries, the
engineering group, said: 'We have yet to see all this talk of improvement
reflected in our UK order books.'
The survey came on the same day as the FT-SE 100 index of leading shares
broke through 3,000 for the first time.
Mr Charles Burton, joint managing director of Business Strategies, said the
report pointed to an upturn, with 'the recovery feeding to more UK regions'
in which output expansion had been relatively slack.
But 'there was no neat pattern' to the gradual strengthening in demand and
output, and the survey indicated that the manufacturing recovery would slow
over the next few months. The survey comes after strong manufacturing and
export growth helped to lift the UK economy in the early part of the year.
With consumer spending growing slowly because of high personal debts,
manufacturing is expected to be an important factor in any sustained upturn.
The relatively downbeat sentiments from the report were echoed by Mr Simon
Duffy, finance director of the Thorn EMI electronics and leisure company,
who said the upturn was 'uneven'. For Mr Andrew Robb, finance director of
Pilkington, the glass company, Britain was 'just bumping up from the
bottom', with a particular question mark over sales prospects in Germany,
while Mr Rod Sellers, chief executive of the British Vita plastics company,
said: 'I am still looking for the green shoots.'
While the report said business optimism among UK manufacturers had
strengthened in the past three months, only in Scotland was the rise in
confidence greater than that seen in a similar survey in April. The latest
poll questioned 1,346 companies between June 25 and July 14.
Commercial vehicle sales fall by 10.8%, Page 6
</TEXT>
